<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>Section 1.4 - Pivots and their influence on solution spaces</title>
  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>Make sure you can answer the following questions:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li><p>What's a free variable? What's a basic variable?</p></li>
      <li><p>What is a pivot position?</p></li>
      <li><p>What is a consistent system?</p></li>
      <li><p>How can you tell that a linear system is inconsistent using the pivot positions of the corresponding augmented matrix?</p></li>
      <li><p>How can you tell a linear system has infinitely many solutions based on the pivot positions of the corresponding coefficient matrix?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Shown below are three augmented matrices in reduced row echelon
  form.  For each matrix, identify the pivot positions and describe
  the solution space in <em>parametric form</em> (if any solutions exist).</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p><m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace=".5in">
    <statement>
      <p>Each of these augmented matrices above has a row in
  which each entry is zero.  What, if anything, does the
  presence of such a row tell us about the solution space to the
  linear system?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1.5in">
    <statement>
      <p>Give an example of a <m>3\times5</m> augmented matrix
  in reduced row echelon form that represents a consistent
  system.  Indicate the pivot positions in your matrix and
  explain why these pivot positions guarantee a consistent
  system.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1.5in">
    <statement>
      <p>Give an example of a <m>3\times5</m> augmented matrix in
  reduced row echelon form that represents an inconsistent
  system.  Indicate the pivot positions in your matrix and
  explain why these pivot positions guarantee an inconsistent
  system.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1.1in">
    <statement>
      <p>How do the pivot positions <term>in an augmented matrix</term> determine whether a linear system is
  consistent or not?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1.5in">
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose we have a linear system for
  which the <em>coefficient</em> matrix has the following
  reduced row echelon form. (The coefficient matrix is where we just don't write the last column of the augmented matrix, just the coefficients of the variables <m>x_1,\dots, x_n</m>.)
  <md>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2  \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0  \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </md>
  Even though we don't have any information about the right-hand side
  of the equations, what can you say about the consistency of the
  linear system?  Explain your thinking.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>The following augmented matrix is in reduced row echelon form.</p>
      <p><m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrrr|r}
      1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m></p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Describe the solution space in parametric form.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>In the solution set a variable is called a <em>free variable</em> if there is no restriction on that value. All other variables are called <em>basic variables</em>. Identify the basic and free variables.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What's the connection between pivot positions and basic/free variables?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>If possible, give an example of a <m>3\times5</m>
  augmented matrix that corresponds to a system of linear equations
  having a unique solution. If it is not possible, explain why.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>If possible, give an example of a <m>5\times3</m>
  augmented matrix that corresponds to a system of linear equations
  having a unique solution. If it is not possible, explain why.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>What condition on the pivot positions guarantees that a system of
  linear equations has a unique solution?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>If a system of linear equations has a unique solution, what can we
  say about the relationship between the number of equations and the
  number of unknowns?  Use the concept of pivot positions to explain
  your thinking.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="1in">
    <statement>
      <p>For what values of the parameter <m>k</m>  is the following system consistent? For which of those values is the solution unique?
	\begin{eqnarray*}
	-x_1 + 2x_2 &amp;=3\\
	2x_1 -4x_2 &amp;=k
	\end{eqnarray*}
 .</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
